<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-486-231  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 486 231.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 24 1990 v12 n39 p32(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>To keep your PC running smoothly, let the power flow. (keephard-disk microcomputers on constantly) (Tech Talk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hard drive-based microcomputers should be left on around the clockto reduce wear and tear on the systems.andP;  Two problems arise fromturning computers on and off with any frequency.andP;  The first ispotential damage from 'inrush current,' the surge of power thatoccurs when an electrical system starts up.andP;  Drive heads andspindles jerk roughly and other cold subsystems, such as CRTfilaments, are severely stressed as they attempt to come on lineand stabilize.andP;  The second negative consequence of turningmicrocomputer systems on and off is the damage done by thermalcycling.andP;  Thermal cycling is the process of the heating andexpanding of the internal parts of an electronic system duringoperation and then contracting as they cool down when powered off.andO;Repeated expansion and contraction spoils the calibration andalignment of such sensitive systems as the drive heads, integratedcircuits and boards.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersMaintenanceUser BehaviorComputersGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>